Key Arguments: The submission argues that the current members of the 47th Parliament are in contempt of the Commonwealth of Australia Constitution and have no right to sit in Parliament.
The author believes that the oath or affirmation taken by the Prime Minister and his Cabinet is unconstitutional and promotes a Republic, which should be decided by a vote of Australians.
The submission claims that Australians do not need ACMA or any government entity to think for them, as they are capable of making their own decisions.
The author emphasizes the importance of freedom and democracy, arguing that Australians have the right to vote and choose what to believe without government interference.
Main Themes: Constitutional adherence and legitimacy of the current Parliament
Opposition to government control over information and decision-making
Emphasis on individual freedom and democratic rights
Criticism of the National Cabinet and its perceived overreach
Notable Quotes: Australians are a freedom loving people who expect those in office to serve the People by respecting, upholding and protecting the Commonwealth of Australia Constitution 9 July 1900.
